Show me the different loops possible in javascript
In JavaScript, there are several loop structures that you can use to repeat a block of code multiple times. Here are some of the most common ones:

1. For Loop: A for loop is used when you want to iterate over a sequence of values and perform an action on each value. The syntax for a basic for loop in JavaScript is:
```
for (initialization; condition; increment/decrement) {
  // code to be executed
}
```
The initialization statement sets the initial value of the loop counter, the condition checks whether the loop should continue, and the increment or decrement statement changes the value of the loop counter after each iteration.

2. While Loop: A while loop is used when you want to repeat a block of code as long as a certain condition is true. The syntax for a basic while loop in JavaScript is:
```
while (condition) {
  // code to be executed
}
```
The condition is checked at the beginning of each iteration and continues to execute the code until it becomes false.

3. Do-While Loop: A do-while loop is similar to a while loop, but it ensures that the code inside the loop is always executed at least once, regardless of whether the initial condition is true or false. The syntax for a basic do-while loop in JavaScript is:
```
do {
  // code to be executed
} while (condition);
```
The condition is checked after each iteration, and the loop continues to execute until it becomes false.

4. For/In Loop: A for/in loop is used when you want to iterate over the keys of an object or array. The syntax for a basic for/in loop in JavaScript is:
```
for (var key in object) {
  // code to be executed
}
```
The loop iterates over each property of the object and assigns it to the current value of the "key" variable.

5. For/Of Loop: A for/of loop is used when you want to iterate over the values of an object or array. The syntax for a basic for/of loop in JavaScript is:
```
for (var value of object) {
  // code to be executed
}
```
The loop iterates over each property of the object and assigns it to the current value of the "value" variable.

6. Labelled Loop: A labelled loop is used when you want to create a named loop that can be called from other parts of your program. The syntax for a labelled loop in JavaScript is:
```
loopName: {
  // code to be executed
}
```
The loopName is an identifier that can be used to refer to the loop in other parts of the program.

These are just a few of the many loop structures available in JavaScript. Each has its own strengths and weaknesses, so you should choose the one that best suits your needs for your particular task.
